    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <opener><dateline><date when="1916-07-17">17 July 1916</dateline></date>
                    <salute>Dear <persName key="harriet_monroe">Harriet</persName>:</salute></opener>
                <p>After minute researches, the amount of the thing seems to be as follows: that <foreign xml:lang="it">“Cavaliers Servente”</foreign> is the correct form. <foreign xml:lang="it">“Cavaliere Servante”</foreign> is the colloquial form. It is so used in <persName key="lord_byron">Byron's</persName> <title key="donJuan" level ="a">“Don Juan,”</title> <date when="1823”>1823;</date>but this is merely a contraction in conversation in which for purposes of speed the final <quote type="italian">“e”</quote> of <foreign xml:lang="it">“Cavaliere”</foreign> was left out. Now, as I am dealing with the eighteenth century, it seems much more likely that the <quote type="italian">“e”</quote> remained in then. At any rate, this is the most correct form, as you can tell anyone who blames you for using it. I am much obliged to you, however, for bringing the matter to my attention, and I shall submit the case to an Italian philologist before my book is published. As I wired you, I prefer to have it stand as it is in the text.</p>
                <p>Also, how soon do you want my review of <persName key="mary_aldis">Mrs. Aldis’s</persName> book? Will the middle of <date when="1916-08">August</date> do?</p>
               <p>I am sorry to have given you such a lot of trouble, but if you would only leave my manuscripts as you find them, it would save you and me a great deal of bother.</p>
                <closer>Affectionately yours,</closer>
                </p>
        </body>
